T’WAS THE MOM BEFORE CHRISTMAS
__
T’was the week before Christmas when all through the house, not a creature was stirring ‘cept for mom scurrying about.

The stockings were hung by the chimney with care; and mom was only hoping someone would help put the candy in there.

The children were nestled all snug in their beds; while visions of apple and lululemon danced in their heads. 

Mom looking ragged from weeks without sleep; she prayed and she begged the universe for 8-hours deep.

When out on her lawn arose such a clatter, she had to pause for a moment to think what was the matter. 

She realized with sadness she missed another year; she was so busy “doing” she never paused to just be here.

She promised herself it would be different this season; but forgot to ask for help or came up with excuses and reasons.

Then suddenly she awoke from her exhausting nightmare; to realize she had a week left and could do it differently from here.

She asked her family for help and made her to-do list much less; giving her just the amount of time to have a small lovely rest.
__
Friends that celebrate Christmas, there is a week left and not all is lost. If you’re exhausted, take a break and declutter your to-do list! Comment below if you need to rethink the last week so you can enjoy them more!

SIMPLIFY YOUR HOLIDAYS
__
With Hanukkah starting today and Christmas in a week, the holiday season is in full swing! Even so, that doesn't mean there isn't time to simplify.

Below are three simply ways you can (still) simplify this holiday season
1. Simplify your traditions - not all traditions are created equal. Find out the ones your family loves the most and keep those. It might be time for others to be decluttered from your list.
2. Simplify the cooking - nothing says everything needs to be cooked from scratch. You're making the food to spend time with your family and friends. If cooking or baking stresses you out, then simplify by buying it.
3. Simplify the wrapping - no need to stay up all hours of the night making the perfect gift wrap unless you love it so. Get others to help or use simpler packaging (like a gift bag!) and open up space on your calendar.
__

LAST-MINUTE CHRISTMAS WREATHS
__
A simple stovetop recipe for Christmas cookie wreaths made fast 💨 
—
I loved these wreaths growing up. What’s a favorite Christmas cookie you have? Let me know in comments 
__
RECIPE
Ingredients: 
1 stick of butter
1/4 tsp of vanilla extract
1/4 tsp of almond extract
4 1/2 cups of corn flakes
1 bag of marshmallows
green food coloring
red cinnamon candies

How to make:
- Melt butter in pan on low heat on stovetop
- Add marshmallows and melt into the butter
- Add vanilla and almond extract
- Add 6-8 drops of green food coloring
- Gently stir in cornflakes until coated
- Use wet hands to pull out balls, put on wax paper and form into wreaths
- Add cinnamon candies for decoration
- Let cool

10-MINUTE CHRISTMAS COOKIES
__
These cute little cookies can be made in under 10 minutes.

Ingredients
Oreo cookies
Vanilla melting wafers in white
Vanilla melting wafers in green
Sprinkles

How to make
- Melt white chocolate - 30 second intervals in microwave stirring at each interval
- Dip oreo in white chocolate and let cool on wax paper
- Melt green chocolate - 30 second intervals stirring at each interval
- Put melted chocolate in piping bag using small circle tip and pipe a tree
- Add sprinkles and let sit

I found decorating 2-3 trees at a time was best to ensure the chocolate didn’t harden in between.

What do I use? CARDBOARD

Starting on one side, put one end of the lights into the slit and then wrap, wrap, wrap around the cardboard until you put the other end in the slits on the other side. Voila!

BIN SELECTION
__
Not all bins are created equal, so it does take some consideration when selecting them for both practical and aesthetic reasons.
__
The challenge with the original bins in the reel is that the height was too high making it difficult to reach your hand in and quickly grab out something you need. Additionally, the bins were not not clear enough or labeled well enough to be able to see what you needed quickly,
__
So, we used a variety of different bins with lower profiles to make it easier to get things in and out. We upped the size of the font on the labels and contrasted them in black and white. We also used clear plastic for decanted items for beauty and ease.
__
Do you see how important bin selection can be to your organizing project a little easier now?

MOMS, YOU DON’T HAVE TO DO IT ALL
__
When our babies are born, we do everything for them. And we should. The problem is that as the kids get older, we keep doing everything for them and it’s no longer helpful for us and them.
__
Yes, most of the stuff we think needs to get done does need to get done. But so often, we have additional choices:
__
1. You can say NO - if you are asked to do something, pause and think about if you really need to (or want to) do it. If you don’t have capacity to do something that your child, spouse, friend or family asks you to do. You can say no. A simple, I’m sorry I don’t have capacity right now or I’m sorry, but I can’t today. I could help in X days.
2. You can delegate it - we can delegate tasks to our children, to our partners and we can hire help to delegate tasks too (cleaning professionals, home organizers, dog walkers, etc).
3. You can delay - many tasks, if we really ask ourselves, can be delayed until a future time. Before you say yes, ask yourself if you can delay it.

__
People often spend more money than they need to organizing because they run out and buy bins to “organize” first. The problem? When you run out to buy bins before you declutter, you are likely spending money on bins to organize that you don’t need.
__
When you declutter first, you get rid of items you no longer need which means you’ll ultimately need fewer bins than you first think. The results are more money in your pocket or more money for higher quality organizing tools.

WHAT IS MENTAL BURDEN (MENTAL LOAD)
___
It is the mental work of keeping a family running. **Women** carry most of the load and are much more likely to handle the “anticipate” (looking ahead) and “monitor” (holding accountable) steps in running a household. This is true even for household tasks assigned to the male in the household.
___
Why does it matter?

The unfair distribution of women holding the family to-do list in their heads, remembering what needs to be done and when, delegating to family members, and making sure they execute their tasks is affecting their mental health.
___
What can we do about it?

1. Acknowledge it. Household “thinking” is actual work. Men need to learn about it and accept that actual household changes are needed to balance the load.

2. Divide and Conquer. Thinking, writing, and holding your partner accountable for the to-do list is NOT real dividing and conquering. Discuss the list together and split the work. One can "sign kids up for school events" while another "manages the weekly carpool" from start to finish.

3. Women, share examples. Give your partner concrete examples of your invisible tasks. For example, if your husband buys the groceries with a list you created after looking through the fridge/pantry for what you need and calls you when he's at the store if he can't find an item - you are owning the mental load. They have the ability to do the full chore.

4. Men, take “you should have asked” out of your venacular. When a man expects his partner to ask him to do things, he views her as the manager of household chores which she determina when and what to do. This unfair distributes the mental load. It's time for male partners to participate fully to share the mental load.

5. Women, reliquish control. You need to be able to trust your partner (and your kids!) to get things done. If you care about something being done a certain way, explain why and why little details matter to you. 

It’s time for all women to understand that the mental clutter and overwhelm they are feeling is not imaginary. It’s real and it’s time to share the load.

MOST COMMON SYSTEM PROBLEMS IN PANTRY
__
The most common elements we see missing when we are called in to help someone create a system in their pantry are:

1. **No clear zones** - putting like items together in a pantry is the first step in creating a system that can stand the test of time. Creating clear zones for subcategories (pasta, grains, snacks, sweets, etc.) makes it easier to find what you need.

2. **Lack of containment** - having bins in a pantry helps to create the zones. Containment also allows you to put smaller items (think bags of rice) together making it easier to find items quickly.

3. **Zero labels** - expecting a family to be able to understand a system without labels is a recipe for a failed system. Labels helps everyone sharing the space to find what they need and help to put groceries away when they are brought it.

Additionally, perfectionists fear of failing can cause them to procrastinate because they fear they cannot complete it perfectly. Perfectionism traits are often linked to mental health issues like anxiety, OCD and chronic stress and a diminished joy of life.

- become aware of perfectionist tendencies (you can’t grow if you don’t become aware enough to make changes)
- make some mistakes (practice makes progress, even with how we learn to work through mistakes!)

3 PANTRY MISTAKES TO AVOID
__
**Mistake No. 1 - not pulling everything out** - while it might seem easier to just move things around, pulling everything out allows you to categorize what you have, see the space with fresh eyes and to clean it before you transform it.

**Mistake No. 2 - skipping the categorizing step** - putting like items with like items is categorizing. Categorizing helps you get a clearer picture of what type and size of bins you will need to create the system. Love snacks? You might need a larger size bin for that category.

**Mistake No. 3 - lack of containment** - containment is putting a category in something that holds the category together - a bin, a basket or a cardboard box. Without containment, the system easily breaks down. Labels are not enough in a pantry. They are important, but without a clearer boundary that the container provides, the system can fall apart quickly.

FOCUS
__
5 reasons you likely are having a hard time focusing … and what to do about it:

1. **You say YES to too much** - when you say yes to too much, your mind can become cluttered thinking of everything you have to do make it more difficult to focus. If you’ve said yes to too much, reprioritize. Delay, delegate or delete items that are not a priority.

2. **You’re a poor time estimator** - if you think something takes 1 hour, but it really takes longer, then you might have a hard time focusing as tasks step on each other. To improve your time estimating, write down how long different tasks take for two weeks. Getting better at estimating allows you to know how much you can say yes too.

3. **No morning routine -** if you dive into your day without any consideration on what you need to do and when, you might find it difficult to stay focused on tasks. A morning routine that includes the items you will focus on for the day makes it easier to focus efforts on those tasks.

4. **Tech distractions (social media, texts ...)** - distractions often hurt our focus and productivity. If you are on deadline or have priorities that must be met, then turn off your notifications so you can minimize distractions and increase focus.

5. **You have undiagnosed Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)** - If you have had focus challenges as long as you can remember, you might have ADHD. Talk to your doctor for testing to determine best next step. And if you are diagnosed, know that the solutions to 1-4 above are still relevant!

3 HABITS TO A **CONSISTENTLY TIDY** KITCHEN
__
The kitchen gets a lot of daily use and therefore can become a hotbed for clutter quickly. If you are tired of the constant mess in your kitchen, here are three things you can do to have a consistently tidy kitchen:

1. **Empty Dishwasher Each Morning** - Running the dishwasher before each night before you head to bed and  unloading it in the morning  allows for everyone to easily (no excuses!) put dirty dishes into the dishwasher.

2. **Put your own food/dishes away after breakfast + lunch** - with an empty dishwasher in the morning, breakfast and/or lunch dishes can easily be rinsed off and put into the dishwasher. Food scraps into the garbage and other food back to its home (eg. refrigerator)

3. **Family after-dinner routine** - when everyone who eats a meal participates in cleaning up after the meal, it takes very little time to clean a whole kitchen. Clearing the table, getting fridge items back to fridge, hand washing pots and pans used, other dishes in dishwasher, spray counters, sweep floors and start the dishwasher! Doing this after-dinner routine gives you a peaceful space before bed and also sets you up for success for the next day.

PEOPLE-PLEASERS
__
It’s taken me time to realize that my people-pleasing ways were hurting me. As I continue to practice putting my needs on the same level as others, I’ve learned a few things. Today I’m sharing my top three ways to stop people pleasing (yes, these take practice!)
__
1. **Look inward + be honest** - Often I say yes to helping someone whose asked me for support before I check in with myself to see if I have the time to support or the emotional bandwidth to support. When I’ve said yes when I really need to say no, I suffer. Next time someone asks you for help, actually think if you can and politely say no when you can’t.

2. **Learn to say no nicely** - For much of my life, I would say yes when I needed to say no to take care of myself. By saying yes when I needed to say no would cause resentment to build up and my relationships have suffered because of it. Practicing taking a moment to decide if something actually works for me first and saying a polite no when it doesn’t has been one of the best self-recovery tools I’ve used.

3. **Set healthy boundaries** - Your instincts are key here. So often we don’t listen to what they are saying to us. When anger, resentment and frustration show up it’s time to check in with yourself and see if it’s time to set boundaries.

FIVE THINGS I WOULDN’T DO AS A HOME ORGANIZER
__
1. I would never have so much stuff in my garage that cars wouldn’t fit. Why? I live in a cold climate and keeping our cars in the garage is a must so we store the minimum we can in the garage.

2. I would never have so much dirty laundry that I’d need to buy new clothes. Why? Having a laundry system that works means less money wasted on buying too many duplicates.

3. I would never have a garbage in every room. Why? Too many garbages means more garbage to collect each week. I keep garbages in the bathrooms, the kitchen, my office and the laundry room. All bedrooms and other living spaces have no garbages.

4. I would never have a hamper in my closet. Why? You don’t have a good pulse on what’s dirty until there are mountains of hampers in every room and then it’s overwhelming. I’ve seen way too many overflowing hampers in homes of families.

5. I would never use unmatched hangers in my closet. Why? They look better and decrease visual clutter.

MATCHING HANGERS - TOP 3 REASONS

1. They **remove visual clutter**: matching hangers hangs all garments at the same height and width removing visual clutter. Less visual clutter = less stress on the brain.

2. They’re **better for your clothes**: using all the same hangers lessen the chance clothes will get snagged on random hangers which can cause garments to lose their shape and even get damaged.

3. They make it **easier to find your clothes**:  When your closet is full of random hangers, garments tend to get “lost” behind others.

**As a BONUS, here are my thoughts on a few important hangers:**

1. **Wood hangers**:  beautiful, eco-friendly and now come in slim sizes, so they are space efficient too!

2. **Rubberized or velvet “sticky” hangers**:  Both great with space-saving designs and hold slippery or small strapped clothes well. Rubberized are easier to take clothes on and off of than velvet.

3. **Acrylic hangers**: Upscale look, but can be very expensive and not eco-friendly.

4. **Metal pant hangers**: Yes, you need them. Hanging pants on shirt hangers is hard to get them off the clothes and doesn’t look as good.

5. **Dry clean hangers**:  They are pretty flimsy as hangers go, so they’re not a favorite of mine. If you just hate the idea of switching out hangers, then try to get the whole closet as dry cleaning to decrease visual clutter.

QUESTIONS FOR DECLUTTERING CLOTHES
__
If you’re having a hard time deciding what stays and what goes in your kitchen, try asking yourself these three questions:

1. **Do you use it?** Poor fitting clothes often result in them not being worn and just take up space in your closet or cause stress when you think about them. For me, these are donates.

2. **Do you love it?** If you don’t love it and you say no to the other questions, then it’s time to let it go. And remember, shame isn’t love and spending a lot of money on it also isn’t love. Only your heart knows what you really love. If other “reasons” are popping up to keep that you’re trying to force into the love bucket, tread carefully. It’s likely a sign of something it could be time to work on.

3. **Is it (actually) useful?** If it’s not useful, then it’s time to let it go. We have enough unhelpful things in our life.
__
For me, if I don’t use it, I don’t love it and it’s not actually useful … bye bye and bye!

5 TIPS FOR A FALL-READY CLOSET
__
The heat finally blew out this week, so sweaters are showing up. Here are 5 things to consider to get a fall-ready closet

1. **Edit first** - review your summer items and tuck them away to sell next year or donate them now. review all Fall/Winter items and sell/donate anything you no longer love. (Always declutter first, organize 2nd!)

2. **Create a home for fashion hats** - we see a lot more fashion hats in fall, so if you’re a hat person - find a home for them. We love using the wall.

3. **Get boots up front** - move your boots to a more accessible place in the closet if they were tucked away in the summer.

4. **Organize your jeans by cut + color** - with the wide variety of jeans we find in every closet, organizing them by color and cut can reduce your searching this fall + winter.

5. **Organize hanging by subcategory** - the fall + winter are all about layers in your closet, so having them organized by subcategories (t-shirts, sweaters, blazers, etc.) allows you to create an outfit more easily.

Daily mail often hits on all three types of clutter - physical (no where to put it), time (no time to do the “to dos”) and mental (negative thoughts toward the tasks inside of the mail).
__
**Sorting mail daily can reduce dread.** 

Why? A little bit each day is more manageable than a huge stack. I like to sort through the mail next to recycling bin since over half of mail can go right into the recycling bin.
__
**Sorting mail into two categories is quick**. 

Sorting your “keepers” into 2 categories of to do + to file is quick. “To do” is ANY task - read it, fill it out, send it in, bills. “To file” are items that need to be filed, but you don’t have time to file right now (titles, health papers, certificates, etc.).
__
**Vertical files marries form + function.** 

Magazine holders take up a little counter space and can be sifted through more easily and when you simplify sorting - you only need 2.
__
**Pro tip: schedule time for to-do’s and to-file’s.** 

When you schedule time to go the to-do’s and to-files, you can focus your mind and body and get the tasks done. Getting into a habit of this helps manage stress.

Q: How to balance family and full time work with caring for aging mom? It’s hard!

A. “Balance” is difficult to attain when both work and life are at max capacity. To be truly balanced, we can only say yes to what we can handle for a given time. As support needs for my parents rose, I had to say no to some things and I had to also get more support and help for my own family.

Setting a timer and putting things away can reduce stress quickly as you begin to show yourself you have the ability to work through the problem.

3. **I ask for help** -  if I can’t delete or delay a task that I’m prioritizing, then I see if I can delegate it - that might be giving the task to a friend or family member or maybe hiring out help.

HELPING KIDS WITH ORGANIZING SYSTEMS
__
How can you help your kids learn and stick to an organizational system? Below are two practical ways:
__
1. **Make sure they understand “the system”** - creating an organizing system for kids is often fail because the system is not actually clear or it’s too difficult of a system. Some examples of where systems fail - bins without labels, bins labeled with words for kids who can’t actually read, bins that contain too broad of categories (eg. toys), bins that contain too narrow of categories (eg. lego heads)

2. **Create a routine** - the second reason organizing systems fail with kids is parents take a “set it and forget it” approach. They create the system and think kids will magically get the motivation to maintain it. They will not. Parents can help by showing leadership to their kids through routines - tuesday clean ups, weekly resets, focused 15-minute clean ups and the list goes on. Use routines that work for your family. For some families, 10 minutes a night works best. For other families, a weekly reset is the key to success.
__
Parents are the leaders of the family and it will take both their leadership (creating routines and holding kids accountable) and their example (putting their own stuff away) to help routines stick.
__

VISUAL CLUTTERS EFFECT ON YOU
__
You might think visual clutter is simply a mess needing to be cleaned up. In reality, visual clutter is making your life more difficult in many ways and affects your brain in a variety of ways, like:

1. **Reduces attention and focus:** when there is too much visual information for the brain to process, it becomes challenging to pay attention to the most important or relevant details.

2. **Slows your processing time:** visual clutter can slow down the brain’s ability to process information making it more difficult to make decisions efficiently, think creatively and solve problems. This is because the brain must work harder to filter out irrelevant information to make sense of the visual scene.

3. **Increasing stress and anxiety:** the brain may interpret cluttered environments as chaotic or disorganized, which can contribute to feelings of unease or tension.

4. **Difficulty concentrating:** visual clutter can lead to visual fatigue, as the eyes and brain struggle to process the abundance of visual stimuli making it difficult to concentrate for extended periods.

5. **Impaired memory:** Excessive visual clutter can make it challenging for the brain to encode and retrieve information effectively. It may hinder memory formation and retention.
__
Look around you right now, what is your visual environment saying to you? Is it calm and peaceful or does it invoke stress + anxiety?

While I’m not really a minimalist per se, I have simplified many areas of my life so I’m able to enjoy them more. In the past I would definitely spent too much time worrying about getting everything “just right” for a holiday than thinking about spending time with the people I love.
__
And while I love to host in a beautiful way, events like Thanksgiving or a dinner party doesn’t take too much extra time because we do these three things:

1. **We elevate the everyday** - we use our everyday everything and just take it up a notch with a plate charger and a napkin ring and maybe some flowers picked from outside.

2. **We use grocery store conveniences** - pre-made crust, take and bake rolls, pre-cut fruit. Whatever can lessen the load and allows you to spend more time with your people is a good thing.

3. **We prep what we can ahead** (and pick recipes that can be prepped ahead) to lessen day of tasks - chopping onions, vegetables, fruit, making pies and other tasks can be done days (sometimes weeks) ahead of time. Breaking up the tasks across many days makes it easier to do.

Wishing you a wonderful Thanksgiving prep season!

__
Sometimes it’s hard to focus when you reflect and it’s why I love to use worksheets almost as a form of guided meditation. The My Desire Life Worksheets are two sheets I go to often with a cup of tea.
__
**How to use them?**

Step 1: Rate your life in 6 areas (work, surroundings, finances, freetime, tribe, health) by shading the wheel to the corresponding ring on the chart. For example, if you rate your work a 6 out of 10, you’d shade in 6 rings. Keep doing this for each area until you’re done.

Step 2: On the now shaded in wheel, make a mark where you want to be. Sometimes, you’re just where you want in that area of your life and other times you might want to move forward differently.

Step 3: Write down a goal for each area as well as practical steps to get to the goal.

How monthly planning has helped me:

Years ago when I was working in corporate, I learned how to plan using a quadrant of importance and urgency. I realized I was spending too much time in Q1 (urgent + important) and not enough time in Q2 (important + not urgent), which was causing me a lot of anxiety and stress.
__
You see, when you spend too much time in Q1, your nervous system is in fight or flight mode and it doesn’t get a chance to rest. If everything is alway urgent and important it is likely that you’re rushing, running around and your mind is following that frantic lead.
__
Taking time (and a deep breath) to sit down and think about (and write it down) the month ahead helps to slow you down and get your thoughts out of your cluttered mind and onto the page.

ORGANIZED BAKING
—
‘Tis the season for holiday baking! Is your kitchen ready?
—
Organizing your baking items takes some of the stress of baking away. Organizing your ingredients and your tools allows you to quickly find what you need and when you’re running low on supplies.
—
Below are 5 ways to organize your biking items

1. **Create a zone** - dedicating a place in your kitchen that all of your baking pans live helps streamline looking for that category

2. **Stand up your pans** - using a divider in your cabinet to stand up your pans makes it smoother to get one out at a time. In this reel, we used the @youcopia divider.

3. **Decant your most used items** - decanting your most used baking items will help the items stay fresher longer and makes it easy for you to stay on top of inventory. Label the sides for cupboards and the top for when you put in drawers.

4. **Create a baking drawer** - If you have a really deep drawer, they can be an excellent place to put your baking items. Baking drawers also allow littles ones to help you out easier as well.

5. **Get decorating items together** - we find that people bake way more than they decorate, so if you separate your decorating out you don’t have to deal with it every time you bake and you know just where it is when you do need to find it!

STEAL MY DECLUTTERING METHOD (FREE CHECKLIST, TOO!)
__
After helping people declutter their homes for many years, here are my top keys to success you can embrace to help you declutter in 2024!

1. **Embrace a helpful mindset** - deciding you’re no longer going to live in the cluttered space and that you’re going to prioritize your time to make decisions and then move the stuff out of the space one item at a time is half the battle.

2. **Declutter by category** - gather up items from one category to make your decision. When you see all of one item together, it’s easier on your brain to decide what you love.

3. **Focus on the keeps** - once you have a category pulled together, focus on the ones you love the most and pull them aside. You’ll quickly see the ones that need to go.

SOLUTIONS TO HOUSE CLUTTER
__
The three big reasons you’re home might be cluttered. Below are some quick tips on how to solve for these challenges:

1. **Too much to manage** - pick one category (I’d recommend starting with clothes) of items in your home and edit it. Keep what you love and say goodbye to what you don’t.

2. **Lack of systems** - A system can be as easy as putting a label on a basket so everyone knows what goes into the bin. Pick one small spot (maybe the front coat closet) and create a system using baskets and labels and communicate the system to your family.

3. **Lack of routines** - even a great system will fall down if you don’t hold people accountable to putting their things away. Routines can help with that. My favorite routine is the weekly reset, which our family does every Sunday. Come join us in stories every Sunday and we can reset our homes together.
